<problem>
<!-- <title>Calculate zeros, critical points, intervals of increase with plot</title> -->

<setup>

<function name='f' variables='x'>(x^2-1)*e^x</function>

<math name='f_poly'>(x^2-1)</math>
<math name='zeros'>-1, 1</math>

<math name='fprime_expanded'>2xe^x + (x^2-1)e^x</math>
<function name='fprime'>(x^2+2x-1) e^x</function>

<math name='fprime_polynomial'>(x^2+2x-1)</math>

<math name='cp1'> -sqrt(2) - 1</math>
<math name='cp2'>  sqrt(2) - 1</math>
<math name='critical_points'>$cp1, $cp2</math>


<subsetOfReals name='left_interval'>(-infinity, $cp1 )</subsetOfReals>
<subsetOfReals name='middle_interval'>($cp1 ,$cp2 )</subsetOfReals>
<subsetOfReals name='right_interval'>($cp2 , infinity)</subsetOfReals>

<math name='f_cp1'>$$f($cp1 )</math>
<math name='f_cp2'>$$f($cp2 )</math>
<point name='point_cp1'>($cp1 ,$f_cp1 )</point>
<point name='point_cp2'>($cp2 ,$f_cp2 )</point>


</setup>


As a warm up, consider the function <m>f(x)= $f </m> that is graphed below.



<graph width='500' height='250' xmin='-5' xmax='3' ymin='-1.5' ymax='2.1' fixAxes>

<copy tname='f' />

