<solution>
  <setup>
<math name='x1'>-3</math>
<math name='fprimex1'>$$fprime($x1 )</math>
<math name='x2'>0</math>
<math name='fprimex2'>$$fprime($x2 )</math>
<math name='x3'>1</math>
<math name='fprimex3'>$$fprime($x3 )</math>
  </setup>

<ol>

<li>
The derivative is <m>\frac{ df }{ dx }= $fprime_expanded = $fprime </m>.
</li>

<li>
The derivative exists everywhere.  Since the exponential function can never be zero, the only way for
<me>\frac{ df }{ dx } = $fprime =0</me>
is for <m>$fprime_polynomial =0</m>.  Plugging this into the quadratic equation we find the critical points are
<m>x=$critical_points </m>, or, if rounding to 5 significant digits, the critical points are <m>x=<round numberdigits="5">$critical_points</round></m>.

<p>Since <m>f(<round numberdigits="5">$cp1</round>)=<round numberdigits="5">$f_cp1</round></m>, the ordered pair is <m><round numberdigits="5">$point_cp1</round></m>.  Since <m>f(<round numberdigits="5">$cp2</round>)=<round numberdigits="5">$f_cp2</round></m>, the ordered pair is <m><round numberdigits="5">$point_cp2</round></m>.

</p>
</li>

<li>
<p>Left interval: <m><round numberdigits="5">$left_interval</round></m></p>

<p>Middle interval: <m><round numberdigits="5">$middle_interval</round></m></p>

<p>Right interval: <m><round numberdigits="5">$right_interval</round></m></p>
</li>

<li>
We could pick for example <m>x=$x1 </m> in the left interval.  Since <m>\frac{ df }{ dx }\Big|_{x=$x1  } = <round numberdigits="5">$fprimex1</round> \gt  0</m>, <m>f</m> is increasing in the left interval.

<p>We could pick for example <m>x=$x2 </m> in the middle interval.  Since <m>\frac{ df }{ dx }\Big|_{x=$x2  } = <round numberdigits="5">$fprimex2</round> \lt  0</m>, <m>f</m> is decreasing in the middle interval.</p>

<p>We could pick for example <m>x=$x3 </m> in the rigth interval.  Since <m>\frac{ df }{ dx }\Big|_{x=$x3  } = <round numberdigits="5">$fprimex3</round> \gt  0</m>, <m>f</m> is increasing in the right interval.</p>

</li>

<li>
Since <m>e^x</m> cannot be zero, <m>f(x)</m> is zero only when <m>$f_poly =0</m>, i.e., when <m>x= $zeros </m>.

<p>The locations of the critical points and roots of <m>f</m> are shown in the following figure.</p>


<graph width='500' height='300' xmin='-5' xmax='3' ymin='-2' ymax='3'  showNavigation='false'>

<copy tname='f' />

<copy fixed stylenumber='2' tname='point_cp1' />
<copy fixed stylenumber='2' tname='point_cp2' />


<point fixed stylenumber='3'>(1, 0)</point>
<point fixed stylenumber='3'>(-1, 0)</point>

</graph>
</li>


</ol>

</solution>


